{"type":"message","id":"87e64677","parentId":"71a7f5e3","timestamp":"2026-03-26T02:40:31.960Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the real situation:\n- Feature max date: 2026-03-10\n- Prediction max date: 2026-03-03\n- Current date: 2026-03-26\n- Live predictions: don't exist\n\nSo the signal is 23 days old, the feature is 16 days old. The current staleness check compares signal (03-03) vs feature (03-10), giving lag = 7 days. Since MAX_SIGNAL_LAG_DAYS = 2, this should trigger staleness.\n\nBut wait, the ACTIVE_TASK says that on 03-24 and 03-25, the script outputs \"买入: set(), 卖出: set()\" and \"信号日期: 2026-03-03\". \n\nThis means the script IS detecting staleness and setting execution_status to \"signal_stale_hold\", which results in empty buy/sell lists. So the logic is working as intended—when the signal lag exceeds the threshold, it falls back to holding positions without generating new trades.\n\nBut looking at the dates more carefully, there's a gap: features were last updated on 03-10, predictions on 03-03, and today is 03-26. The script is correctly flagging this as stale and preventing trades. The real problem is that the user experience is confusing—they're seeing empty signal lists without understanding why the system has stopped trading. The fix needs to focus on making this clearer in the output and dashboard rather than changing the underlying behavior.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the specific changes needed: the trading script should add a current_date comparison to better explain the staleness, the report and dashboard need more prominent warnings when in stale mode, and the summary JSON already has the right fields but they're not being displayed clearly enough. Let me implement these visibility improvements.","thinkingSignature":"d38b3251efff5fa93aa56cb5048f3aa67e5709e1c744e704c27bd0037da3e42e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_n4nyw5kc9nnr_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nim